text: If Pixar pulls this off, it could be something amazing. If they don't...well then I will be really disappointed.Â   This sounds like a nightmare for the writers. Everything that happens in her mind has to make some sort of sense because it has to connect with real-world things in a logical way. If done wrong, it could just seem like her mind is insane, or that what happens in her mind has no connection to her real-life actions. They have to create rules for this world that we can believe. If they don't get it just right, the audience could constantly call into questions the rules of the story and think "wait...this doesn't add up," or, "What's going on, again?" If they do it well, though, this could be a really thoughtful movie with a lot of depth, where everything happens for a reason and there's meaning in every action of every scene.

text: Ok, I really want to see this. Not just because of the original story concept, but to see how Joy and Sadness work off each other. Also, I'm really curious to see how they justify being sad. From the looks of the trailer, it seems that Joy is sort of the "big dog" in Riley's emotions and Sadness just wants to feel as important and special. When she touched one of the core memories, I can't help but think that maybe it was originally a sad memory, but then Joy made it a happy one, so that when Sadness touched it again, it took on it's true form. (Something like that, I don't know). Â   Really, Sadness is the only emotion that's sort of hard to defend. Joy is obvious because happiness is positive energy. Fear stops you from doing foolish things (i.e. you don't run out into traffic because the thought of being hit by a car is a scary thought. Common sense, I know, but it's linked to fear). Â Anger, when controlled, can actually be a confidence boost and make you want to stand up for what you believe in. Like being angry against a bully. Disgust...well, I guess disgust can be like fear where it stops you from doing stupid stuff and can lead you to wiser choices. But Sadness can be tricky. I mean, no one LIKES being sad, unless it's a stress relief to cry. Anyone care to comment? (Not trying to star a flame war. I'm just curious to see what people say.)Â

text: Okay, so I'm excited for this movie. I think it's definitely very emotional and deep if you're open minded and can interpret things on a deeper level. So Sadness seems to be the main emotion that nobody really likes, although Joy tries to be friendly. So when Joy and Sadness get lost, Riley mostly feels Anger, Fear and Disgust. In my mind, I think this shows that when people are so down they try to block out a certain emotion, such as joy, love, sadness, etc., these emotions almost kinda get lost deep inside you, causing your other emotions to take over instead. For instance, if you're broken hearted and you block out the emotion of love, then when another situation comes up where somebody likes you, then you're angry because you don't want to get feelings, or you're fearful because you think they'll leave or you're confused of why they even bother to acknowledge you. So blocking out one emotion enhances your others to take over. All of them together can balance each other out. You need them all. I think that's what this movie is meant to portray on a deeper level.

text: Ok but guys, Riley's mom's emotions are all strictly female and her dad's are all male. But Riley has male and female emotions which makes sense because she has genes from both her parents. So she has anger and fear from her dad (both identical to the ones her father has) and then sadness and grossness (I think) which are the same as her mothers. But then there is happiness who is someone that neither her mom or her dad has so it could mean that maybe happiness is gender fluid or transgender? text: To the people who ask why they chose the emotions they chose, like disgust, etc. There's a reason why. In Psychology, you learn that a human is born with 6 natural emotions Â - Happiness, Sadness, Anger, Fear and Disgust, as well as Surprise. They are programmed in your brain right away and those are the only 6 you start off with. All other feelings, such as jealousy, envy, hatred, anxiety, mischievousness, etc. even love are learned emotions you pick up growing up.

text: INSIDE OUT - MOVIE REVIEW (Spoiler Alerts!)   I watch it and it was beyond my comprehension. This movie is so smart, funny, insightful & sad (like, seriously sad... T.T). I think this cartoon is not just an ordinary kids movie, rather, more suitable for grown-ups, especially those who struggling with their own crowded minds. I read somewhere, some psychiatric even try to connect the message from this movie with Autism and Depression. Tough subject for kids cartoon, right?   There's one cute character named Bing-Bong, he not even mentioned in the trailer, yet his part is so grandiose & touching. Prepare yourself, Bing-Bong gonna put a big painful lump in your chest & lung while you watch (or can't even).   There's so many sad moments in this movie, too sad for kids, yet, I think, it will relieving for the adults. Since we don't have many chance to cry nowadays... Nevertheless, the sad parts is equal with the funny & happy parts. There's many smart dialogue & plot that you can't even point out. Who knows a mind of 11-year old girl named Riley could be that astonishing heartbreaking...?   I love Joy so much, and her joy in this movie isn't the ignorant one. She try to be happy all the time for the sake of Riley. So when Joy became sad at the centre of the movie, you really need to grab lots of tissues, FAST.   Whoever you are, you should watch Inside Out: Highly recommended, it's funny, shocking, happy, sad, smart & even terrifying in some pivotal parts. 10/10 for Pixar. Love it!!

text: Just saw this flick and I got to say that this is one of the best movies I've seen in quite some time. Beats Age of Ultron hands down. Anybody out there identify a lot with the subject matter in this movie? Like just about everything?  Kind of sucks when you go with a group of people to the movies and they don't get the same thing you get out of it so you can't really engage in deep conversation about it with anyone besides the funny and sad parts. It's as if people in general will get some sort of buzzkill talking about heavy subjects, like its taboo. Like we just want to keep it superficial. Not often can a movie get you reflecting on your life while bringing out a multitude of emotions that are actually depicted as animated characters. This is how "Inside Out" is a one of a kind and truly unique film to me. Yes, children will enjoy it but adults will get the most out of it, surprisingly.

text: So here is my life (You can ignore this comment if you want):  I started my life in Canada. The people there were great, and everything was perfect. I made a lot of niceÂ friendsÂ and had a lot of fun.I made almost all of my good memories there. InsteadÂ of hockey, I've developed an eager passion for soccer. I've played peewee soccer for about a year, andÂ it was pretty fun toÂ meet new peopleÂ on the soccer team. We lived there for aboutÂ 12 years, until we took an unexpected turn and moved to Korea. At first, I was excited, but i was also sad for having to lose my friends that i've known for a lifetime. I tried to keep positive, but things took a serious downhill overtime. As soon as school started, I was all alone. The people there were mean and racists. Soon, I starting to get depressed, lonely, and even had some suicidal thoughts. One time, I couldnt take it anymore and spent about a month on getting plane tickets and escaping to Canada. But i knew i couldnt do it, so i just decided to stay in Korea. Is been 3 years now, and I've lost my passion for soccer, lost all self confidence, and have depression, anxiety, social issues, and lonliness. I'm 15 now, and have lasted 3 years in hell.  This is why i can connect to the movie "Inside out" so much.

text: For you guys wondering, the people inside her head are boys and girls because she has some of her father and some of her mother. They are in fact younger versions (like her father's anger in the other trailer has a moustache but otherwise is identical to Riley's anger). It's like genes, and she will probably develop female ones later in life, after puberty. Puberty is also about finding yourself (what if one were to turn out transgender, you need gender options). It's logical, because she is not yet fully female.

text: I'm just wondering why is Desire not among the cartooned emotions in the film Inside out. The film has Joy, Sadness, Fear, Anger, and Disgust but there is no Desire. (No spoiler here, they were all introduced in the trailers.) The filmmakers may justify that they need to limit the characters but Desire is such an important emotion to be left out. Desire, drive, or passion helps in steering our thoughts and actions. Desire can be an unruly emotion that often lands us in mischief if unguarded, but it can also be a driving force for us to achieve something if we just channel it positively. What if there is Desire in Inside Out? How would they draw him/her? How would the story go?

I was blown away by it's depth, and authenticity to the human experience, by it's music and character. And now, despite the newest film The Good Dinosaur not offering much in it's trailers, I have no doubt it's going to be spectacular. Can't judge a movie on it's jacket, I suppose.

text: I hope someone is listening!  This sort of animation is based on certain psychological factors with which we interpret the world!  If you parents will look you will see certain recognizable categories of facial configuration.  Of course you know that just because someone looks a certain way, doesn't mean they ARE a certain way!  However anyone who has studied the Nazi approach to classifying individuals will know that is exactly how they viewed people.  "If you don't look Aryan then you are inferior!".   These advanced animations have the potential to create perceptions in the minds of children which are shaped by the animator.  In other words the animator can choose what ever facial characteristics he or she chooses to be the villain or the hero or what ever!  Be careful what you allow your kids to watch!  The thought is, mind control!

text: On some level, Inside Out does a somewhat admirable job at trying to explain to children (and I guess, easily impressed adult children) how emotions work... sort of. It tries to explain that our emotions control our mental faculties, that we think BECAUSE of our emotions.   This line of thinking is far too naive.   What old Pixar was really good at doing, is telling a story that had both a simplicity that made children understand and a maturity which reflects the reality of the world. It was exceedingly clever and charming and it taught children on how the real world works. Inside Out however, is too fictitious to be taken seriously, and not fictitious enough to be taken lightly.   First off, to think that our thoughts and minds and behaviors are controlled by emotions is just patently wrong. Feelings are not reality. Humans are not a manifestation of feelings, the environment is not built upon emotions. Emotions are a symptom of how our minds process our environment.   We are happy when something good happens to us, we get angry when we are transgressed, we are sad when we lost something of value to us, we are disgusted by things that would harm us, we are afraid of things that we don't understand. Emotions are reactions, not actions.   So right off the bat, the premise of the film is already off. Things are not made any better with the plot. The film centers around Joy, (an emotion of 12 year old girl Riley) having forced to confront a life-altering change and going through a coming of age journey, learning things about Riley, about Joy itself and of other emotions Anger, Disgust, Fear and specifically Sadness  This journey is something that Riley should go through herself, by learning to deal with overwhelming emotions, rather than represented by proxy through Joy. Instead, the movie shows Riley simply "feel" things that are happening to her, rather than understand what's going on and take responsibility and accountability for her own wellbeing - which is the essence of growing up. By the end of the movie, Riley herself didn't learn anything, she didn't have any growth.
